Once we've completed the differentiation, we can arrange the equation so $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$ is isolated:

$\begin{align}
6x^2-5y-5x\cdot\dfrac{dy}{dx}-2y\cdot\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=0
\\\\
\dfrac{dy}{dx}(-5x-2y)&=-6x^2+5y
\\\\
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=\dfrac{-(6x^2-5y)}{-(5x+2y)}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{6x^2-5y}{5x+2y}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(2,4)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=-\dfrac{1+2y}{2x-2y}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{1+2(4)}{2(2)-2(4)}\qquad\gray{x=2,\,\,y=4}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{9}{-4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{9}{4}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(1,0)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=\dfrac{3y-2x}{2y-3x}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{3(0)-2(1)}{2(0)-3(1)}\qquad\gray{x=1,\,\,y=0}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{-2}{-3}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2}{3}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(-1,2)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=-\dfrac{6x^2+2xy}{x^2+2y}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{6(-1)^2+2(-1)(2)}{(-1)^2+2(2)}\qquad\gray{x=-1,\,\,y=2}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{2}{5}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(1,2)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=\dfrac{3y-2x}{3y^2-3x}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{3(2)-2(1)}{3(2)^2-3(1)}\qquad\gray{x=1,\,\,y=2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{4}{9}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(2,1)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=\dfrac{2x-3x^2y}{x^3+2y}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2(2)-3(2)^2(1)}{(2)^3+2(1)}\qquad\gray{x=2,\,\,y=1}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{-8}{10}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{4}{5}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(2,0)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=-\dfrac{1+3y}{4y^3+3x}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{1+3(0)}{4(0)^3+3(2)}\qquad\gray{x=2,\,\,y=0}
\\\\
&=-\dfrac{1}{6}
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(1,2)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=\dfrac{2xy-4}{3y^2-x^2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{2(1)(2)-4}{3(2)^2-(1)^2}\qquad\gray{x=1,\,\,y=2}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{0}{11}
\\\\
&=0
\end{align}$

Now we can plug the point $(0,-1)$ into the expression for $\dfrac{dy}{dx}$.

$\begin{align}
\dfrac{dy}{dx}&=\dfrac{y-3x^2}{4y-x}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{(-1)-3(0)^2}{4(-1)-0}\qquad\gray{x=0,\,\,y=-1}
\\\\
&=\dfrac{-1}{-4}
\\\\
&=\dfrac14
\end{align}$
